The real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that parallels the exodus of the Israelites led by Moses from Egypt.
I grew up with this.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven out of their southern bases by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government in the early 1930s.
Pursued and harassed by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and rugged grasslands, with Mao steering the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of perseverance, courage, and hope, despite incredibly poor prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only one-fifth of the original 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, badly wounded, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
To what extent does China's founding myth hold up to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the start of the Long March, I set out to trace its footsteps.
It remains a terrifying journey through regions that have changed little since then, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I located 40 of them and spoke with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or made it to the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, barely taller than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: His father was arrested and would not be released until Huang agreed.
He thought about fleeing, but stayed out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many ran away.
Six weeks into the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major engagement of the army on the march.
But no more than 15,000 died in the battle; the rest disappeared.
Another battle, at the Dadu River, stands at the center of the Long March legend. Supposedly, 22 brave men overpowered a regiment of nationalist troops guarding the Luding bridge with machine guns, clearing the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu was the most important event on the Long March, and this is how it is still celebrated today.
But documents I have seen suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu initially told party historians a completely different story. "The matter was not as complicated as people later portrayed it," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should adhere to the truth."
How it is portrayed is another matter."
So the legend continues.
There was only some bickering over the Dadu River.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
In return, he later received a ministerial position in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were going.
There were constant discussions about the final goal.
When they met in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the icy cold.
The women were ordered to turn around and return home because there was not enough food.
About a month after the merger of the three Red Armies, the party decided that the Long March had to continue.
However, it saved the abduction of Chiang Kai-shek by the general whom Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was ended.
Not for the 21,000 men and women of the West Legion, however.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, which was led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's arch-rival, and had the mission to cross the western Chinese border to seek help from Russia.
But Mao gave them contradictory orders, so they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped on barren land where survival was difficult, they were wiped out by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border; the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Yet it is missing from official history.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was enough to make her appear a traitor in the eyes of the party and to deny all the years she had dedicated to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, despairing, and persevered.
Hunger drove the soldiers to take hostages to extort ransom.
The executions continued until practically no officers were left to take command in battles.
When the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with the help of communist propaganda.
They bore their suffering with a bravery and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other peoples.

What drove them to do it?
I asked one of the top generals what he knew about communism back then. “I didn’t know then what I don’t know today,” he replied. “I even doubt that Mao himself really knew what it was.” For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, the hope of a just and progressive society.
No one may have known – or could know – how much more suffering lay ahead, how great the sacrifice would be, and how enormous the gap between dream and reality would be.
